individual.name: William I ,The Conqueror
individual.note: Survived his father as (William II) Duke of Normandy 1035, conquered Maine 1063, Obtained crown of England by conquest 14, Oct. 1066. Crowned at Westminster Abbey by Ealdred, Archbishop of York, 25 Dec. 1066. He died at the Priory of St. Gervais, near Rouen and was buried at the Abbey of St. Stephen Caen, which he founded.

individual.note: Lord of Sully jure uxoris, excluded from succession to Blois and Chartres for lack of capacity. He had 3 sons and two daughters by his only wife Agnes.

individual.note: Widow of Louis II Duke of Longueville, and eldest daughter of Claude I de Lorraine, Duke of Guise.

individual.name: Charles II/Stuart
individual.note: Duke of Cornwall and Duke of Rothsay, etc. at birth, declared (but never crowned) Prince of Wales 1638, crowned King of Scots at Scone 1 Jan, 1651, lived in exile in France, Germany and Holland 1651-60. Crowned by William Juxon, Archbishop of Canterbury.

burial.place: Church, St. Thomas's, Isle of Wight

individual.name: Henrietta Anne/Stuart
individual.note: Married Phillipe who was her 1st cousin. She had one son and three daughters. The representation of the Royal Houses of Stuart, Tudor, Plantagenet and Normandy is vested in the descendants of the Princess Henrietta, Duchess of Orleans, but being Roman Catholics they were excluded from the succession to the throne by the Act of Settlement 1788(?).

individual.name: Egbert
individual.note: Expelled from England "to the land of the Franks" by Offa, King of Mercia and Beorhtric, King of Wessex in 789?. Acknowledged in Kent, Surrey, Sussex, Essex and East Anglia after his victory over the Mercians at Ellendun (near Wroughton, Wilts) in 825. Conquered Mercia in 829 and reckoned as the eighth Bretwalda (Ruler of Britain).

individual.name: Aethelwulf
individual.note: Sub-King of Kent, Essex, Sussex, and Surrey from 825-839. Survived his father in 839, resigned Wessex to his son Ethelbald in 855, retaining Kent, Sussex and Essex.

burial.place: New Minster, then Hyde Abbey, Winchester

individual.name: Aethelred II, The Unready (The_Redeless)
individual.note: Crowned at Kingston-upon-Thames in 979, he later fled to Normandy after the Danish invasion in the autumn of 1013. He was restored to his throne upon the death of Sweyn, Feb 1014. [His regain of the throne is not shown in the Begin Reign-End Reign Events, only the initial reign. (ph)]

individual.name: Elesa
individual.note: According to the Anglo-Saxon Chronicles, Cerdic came to Britain with his son Cynric and five ships in 495, obtained the kingdom of the West Saxons in 519, obtained posession of Isle of Wight in 530.

individual.name: Cerdic
individual.note: Some authorities claim that Cynric is the son of Creoda, son of Cerdic. It appears that he reigned jointly with Cerdic until 534 when Cerdic died. He gave the Isle of Wight to his (or Cerdic's) two nefan (grandsons or nephews) Stuf and Withgar.

individual.name: Ceawlin
individual.note: According to Bede Ceawlin was the second acknowledged overlord (Bretwalda) of the Southern English. He either associated his nephew Ceol in the kingdom or was deposed by him in 591.

individual.name: Cutha
individual.note: Killed in battle as he fought against Britons with his brother, King Ceawlin.

individual.name: Ceol, or Ceolric
individual.note: Reigned jointly with his uncle, King Ceawlin and survived him.

individual.name: Ceolwulf
individual.note: Spent his entire reign fighting the Angles, the Welsh, the Picts, or the Scots.

individual.name: Cynegils

baptism.place: Christianity, by Birinus, Bishop of Dorch.

individual.note: Was converted to Christianity and baptised by Birinus, Bishop of Dorchester in 635.

individual.name: Cenwalh
individual.note: Expelled from Wessex by Penda, King of Mercia in 645 and lived in exile in East Anglia until 648. He was baptised in 646 and founded the Old Minster at Winchester in 648. Married 1st the sister of Penda, King of Mercia whom he repudiated in 645. He married Seaxburh in 645.

individual.name: Centwine
individual.note: Was overthrown and probably killed by Caedwalla. His wife was the 2nd wife of Ecgfrith, King of Northumbria.

individual.name: Caedwalla
individual.note: Abdicated and went to Rome in 688 where she was baptised by the name of Peter by Pope Sergius I.

individual.name: Ine
individual.note: Founded the monastery of Glastonbury, abdicated and went to Rome in 726.

individual.name: Aethelheard
individual.note: From the lineage of Cerdic. Went to Rome with his wife Frithugyth in 737.

individual.name: Cuthred
individual.note: From the lineage of Cerdic. had issue: Cynric who was killed in 748.

individual.name: Sigeberht
individual.note: From the lineage of Cerdic. Deposed by Cynewulf "for unlawful actions" and was stabbed by a herdsman at Privett, near Petersfield, Hants.

individual.name: Cynewulf
individual.note: From the lineage of Cerdic. Surprised and killed at Merantum (Merton, Surrey?) by Cyneheard, the brother of his predecessor, Sigeberht.

individual.name: Beorthric
individual.note: From the lineage of Cerdic. Accidently poisoned by his wife in 802.

individual.name: Cwichelm
individual.note: Associated in the kingdom with his father from 626.

individual.name: Cuthred
individual.note: Baptised at Dorchester by Bishop Birinus in 639, apparently associated in the kingdom with his grandfather and uncle.

individual.name: St. Egelwine, or Ethelwine
individual.note: According to William of Malmesbury she was venerated at Athelney.

individual.name: Oswald
individual.note: Fought with King Aethelheard (probably contesting the succession) in 728.

individual.name: Mul
individual.note: Laid waste to Kent and the Isle of Wight with his brother King Caedwalla in 686 and was burned to death in Kent in 687.

individual.name: Cenred
individual.note: A sub-King of Wessex according to Florence of Worcester.

individual.name: Eafa
individual.note: May have met a princess and heiress of the Royal House of Kent (the Oiscings) and had the following children.

individual.name: Cuthburh
individual.note: Founder of the monastic community at Wimborne. She separated from her husband "during their lifetime".

individual.name: Cuthwulf (Possibly same as Cutha)
individual.note: Fought against the Britons
